SCENE 6.1 - WHAT IS GLOBAL MARKETING?

VISUAL: Dramatic transition: Small village market expanding to global. World map with company expansion visualization. Standardization vs. Adaptation spectrum animation. Global marketing mix diagram with international icons.

NOTE: Camera pulls back from village to town to city to India to world. EPIC scale.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
(Male, sophisticated, global perspective)

Now we move from the local to the global.

What happens when a business decides to take its products beyond its borders? When it moves from serving one country to serving the world? That's Global Marketing.

But here's the critical challenge: Should you standardize or adapt?

The Standardization vs. Adaptation Dilemma:

On one end, you have standardization: Offer the same product, same message, same strategy worldwide. This gives you economies of scale, consistent branding, and operational efficiency.

On the other end, you have adaptation: Customize your product, message, and strategy for each market. This respects local cultures, meets specific needs, and resonates better—but it's expensive and complex.

The reality? Most successful global companies find a balance. They standardize what they can and adapt what they must.

This isn't theoretical. In the next video, we'll look at two masters of global marketing: Nike and Domino's. And we'll examine the eight critical challenges companies face when going global.

But first, let's understand why companies go global in the first place.

VISUAL NOTE: World map with connection points (animated). Standardization vs. Adaptation spectrum with markers. Global marketing mix diagram with icons.

---
SCENE 6.2 - BENEFITS OF GLOBAL MARKETING

VISUAL: Five benefits list with animated icons. Economies of scale visualization. Knowledge transfer diagram. Financial diversification chart. Risk distribution pie chart.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
(Continuing)

Why do companies go global? The benefits are substantial.

Benefit 1: Economies of Scale. When you serve large market segments across multiple countries, you can produce at massive scale. Apple designs one iPhone but sells it worldwide. The R&D cost is spread across hundreds of millions of units.

Benefit 2: Knowledge Transfer. Operating globally allows you to transfer experience and know-how across countries. McDonald's perfected operational efficiency in the US and transferred it globally.

Benefit 3: Access to Tough Customers. Marketing globally exposes you to the world's most demanding customers. Indian IT companies learned by serving demanding US and European clients.

Benefit 4: Financial Diversification. When you operate in multiple markets, you're not dependent on one economy. If one market slows down, others may thrive.

Benefit 5: Exploiting Changing Financial Circumstances. Global companies can take advantage of currency fluctuations, tax regimes, and economic conditions across markets.

These benefits explain why companies aspire to go global. But the path is not easy. In Video 2, we'll explore the eight critical challenges of global marketing, using real-world examples from Nike and Domino's.

VISUAL NOTE: Apple iPhone global sales visualization. McDonald's global operations map. Infosys global delivery centers. Currency fluctuation impact chart. Risk diversification diagram.

